{"cursor":"7123","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"{{Infobox artist\n| bgcolour = #6495ED name = CecÃ­lia Meireles image = imagesize = alt = caption =\n| birth_name = CecÃ­lia Benevides de Carvalho Meireles birth_date = birth_place =\n| Rio de Janeiro death_date = death_place = Rio de Janeiro nationality =\n| Brazilian field = Poet, Educator training = movement = Modernism works =\n| patrons = influenced by = influenced = awards = elected = website =\n}}\n\n'CecÃ­lia Benevides de Carvalho Meireles' (Rio de Janeiro, 1901â1964) was a\nBrazilian writer and educator, known principally as a poet. She is a canonical\nname of Brazilian Modernism, one of the great female poets in the Portuguese\nlanguage, and is widely considered the best poetess from Brazil, though she\ncombatted the word \"poetess\" because of gender discrimination.\n\nShe traveled in the Americas in the 1940s, visiting the United States, Mexico,\nArgentina, Uruguay and Chile. In the summer of 1940 she gave lectures at the\nUniversity of Texas, Austin. She wrote two poems about her time in the capital\nof Texas, and a long (800 lines) very socially aware poem \"USA 1940\", which was\npublished posthumously. As a journalist her columns (crÃ´nicas, or chronicles)\nfocused most often on education, but also on her trips abroad in the western\nhemisphere, Portugal, other parts of Europe, Israel, and India (where she\nreceived an honorary doctorate).\n\nAs a poet, her style was mostly neosymbolist and her themes included ephemeral\ntime and the contemplative life. Even though she was not concerned with local\ncolor, native vernacular, or experiments in (popular) syntax, she is\nconsidered one of the most important poets of the second phase of the\nBrazilian Modernism, known for nationalistic vanguardism. As a teacher she did\nmuch to promote educational reforms and advocated the construction of\nchildren's libraries. Between 1935 and 1938 she taught at the short-lived federal-\ndistrict university in Rio.\n","linknr":165,"url":"Cecília_Meireles","recorded":1375081805,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Cec%C3%ADlia_Meireles&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Cec%C3%ADlia_Meireles&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.rtlcite%2Cwikihiero%7Cext.uls.nojs%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=startup&only=scripts&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/geoiplookup","//meta.wikimedia.org","#mw-navigation","#p-search","/wiki/Rio_de_Janeiro","/wiki/Brazil","/wiki/Modernism","/wiki/Rio_de_Janeiro","/wiki/Brazil","/wiki/Writer","/wiki/Educator","/wiki/Poet","/wiki/Modernism","/wiki/Portuguese_language","/wiki/Gender_discrimination","/wiki/Americas","/wiki/United_States","/wiki/Mexico","/wiki/Argentina","/wiki/Uruguay","/wiki/Chile","/wiki/University_of_Texas","/wiki/Austin","/wiki/Journalist","/wiki/Education","/wiki/Portugal","/wiki/Israel","/wiki/India","/wiki/Honorary_doctorate","/wiki/Neosymbolism","/wiki/Time","/wiki/Life","/wiki/Nationalism","/wiki/Vanguardism","/wiki/Teacher","/wiki/Libraries","/wiki/University","/w/index.php?title=Cec%C3%ADlia_Meireles&action=edit&section=1","/wiki/File:Cec%C3%ADlia_Meireles_em_Lisboa.JPG","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/cd/Cec%C3%ADlia_Meireles_em_Lisboa.JPG/205px-Cec%C3%ADlia_Meireles_em_Lisboa.JPG","/wiki/File:Cec%C3%ADlia_Meireles_em_Lisboa.JPG","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.22wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","/wiki/Sonnet","